[p 
	"The TASVideos record 
	[a href=/1860M 
		"movie
	]a
	" for 
	[em 
		"Pokémon: Yellow Version
	]em
	" uses heavy glitches that lead to Ash cataloging every Pokémon in slightly over a minute.  Is there any way to get more ridiculous than that?  In this run, using nothing but the Game Boy buttons and tool-assisted precision, the game is made to 
	[a class=extlink href=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arbitrary_code_execution rel=nofollow 
		"run an arbitrary program
	]a
	".  For details on how this was achieved, see the 
	[a href=/3894S 
		"author's comments
	]a
	".
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"This movie improves upon 
	[a href=/2187M 
		"its predecessor
	]a
	" by never having to leave Ash's room to gain full control of execution flow. However, that movie has a very different kind of 
	[a class=extlink href=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Payload_%28computing%29 rel=nofollow 
		"payload
	]a
	" at the end, and is worth watching as well. Both movies apply the idea that TASing is 
	[a href=/2380M 
		"programming input
	]a
	" rather than playing the game.  For a list of more runs that embody this idea, see 
	[a href=/forum/p/345831#345831 
		"this post
	]a
	".
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"As this run was submitted on March 14 - "
	[a class=extlink href=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pi_Day rel=nofollow 
		"Pi Day
	]a
	"", it contains many, many references to π. See how many you can find!
	$LF
]p
